  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA304-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiyātu neṭuṅ kālam vantoḻuka vāṟṟāḷākiya talaimakaḷ vaṉpoṟai (ER, ET, EV: vaṉpuṟai) etirmoḻintatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE, who was unable to bear it when [HE] was coming for a long time without marrying,  said in the face of encouragement.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA304">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vāraṉ meṉṟiṉaip pularvukkuraṉ māntic</l>
<l>            cāral varaiya kiḷaiyuṭaṉ kuḻīi</l>
<l>            vaḷiyeṟi vayiriṟ kiḷiviḷi payiṟṟu</l>
<l>            naḷiyiruñ cilampi ṉaṉmalai nāṭaṉ</l>
<l>            puṇariṟ puṇarumā reḻilē piriyiṉ</l>
<l>            maṇiyiṭai poṉṉiṉ māmai cāyave</l>
<l>            ṉaṇinalañ citaikkumār pacalai yataṉā</l>
<l>            lacuṇaṅ kolpavar kaipō ṉaṉṟu</l>
<l>            miṉpamun tuṉpamu muṭaittē</l>
<l>            taṇkamaḻ naṟuntār viṟalōṉ mārpē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">When the man from a land of good mountains with vast big slopes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the parrots repeat [their] sound as a horn blown by the wind,</l>
<l rend="indent2">crowding together with [their] relations from the slopy(?) mountains,</l>
<l rend="indent2">feeding on the drying ear of the upright(?) soft millet,</l>
<l rend="indent">unites [with me],</l>
<l rend="indent4">grace itself unites.</l>
<l rend="indent4">When he separates,</l>
<l rend="indent">[my] darkness, as gold inlaid with sapphires, being exhausted,</l>
<l>pallor wastes my adorning beauty.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Therefore,</l>
<l>it well possesses pleasure and distress,</l>
<l rend="indent3">as the hands of those who kill the Acuṇam,<note place="foot">Here we find a complex and allusive image that is only comprehensible when we know the mythology connected with the <term xml:lang="ta">Acuṇam</term> (not told before the medieval commentaries): it is an animal strongly attracted by music and of very sensitive ear (cf. NA 244, AN 88). Hunters who want to kill it, play soft music from lute or flute, and when it comes close to listen they start beating the drum, which will immediately kill it.</note></l>
<l>the chest of the victorious man with cool fragrant scented garland.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
